[normal]Written evidence submitted by BDR Termea (HOT44)
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]BDR Thermea Group was 
[normal]delighted to
[normal] see publication of the Heat Strategy by DECC which sets out how heating in the UK could be decarbonised by 2050. We believe that the potential benefits to the low carbon economy and UK economic competitiveness from successful implementation are significan
[normal]t.
[normal]Through our well-known brands such as Baxi, Potterton and Heatrae, BDR Thermea empl
[normal]oy over 1,500 people in the UK.
[normal]BDR Thermea
[normal] support
[normal]s
[normal] the decarbonisation of UK heating. However the way in which it is achieved must recognise and address the unique feat
[normal]ures of the UK market. A bespoke approach that plays to consumer preferences, our national infrastructure assets and the strengths of the existing heating sector is required. 
[normal]We are investing in the technologies that could enable such a transformation incl
[normal]uding, Heat Recovery, Micro-Combined Heat and Power, Gas Heat Pumps, Solar Heating and Electric Heat Pumps.
[normal]It is vital to ensure implementation of the Heat Strategy supports the
[normal] manufacturing 
[normal]sector and drives innovation an
[normal]d employment growth in the UK al
[normal]ongside decarbonisation and bill reductions.
[normal]GHPs are an established technology in Europe but RHI 
[normal]support
[normal] on par with other renewable heating 
[normal]technologies
[normal] is essential to provide the necessary incentive, exposure and certainty to start the GHP market in the UK. 
[normal]RHI support would allow G
[normal]HPs to achieve the strategic potential foreseen in DECC’s Heat Strategy and enable prompt decarbonisation and renewable gai
[normal]ns even i
[normal]f
[normal] gas utilisation persists.
